		<TR><TD ALIGN="CENTER" colspan="3">
		
		<h3><FONT FACE="ARIAL,HELVETICA">GALLERIA GOES GOURMET TUESDAY NIGHTS IN APRIL </font></H3>
		</TD></TR>
		<TR><TD>&nbsp;</td></tr>
		<TR><TD colspan="3">
		<FONT FACE="ARIAL,HELVETICA" SIZE="2"><B><FONT size=3><FONT face=Arial>
<P>ROSEVILLE </B>&#8211; This April marks the first annual Galleria Goes Gourmet celebration. Hosted on The Promenade at Galleria at Roseville and held every Tuesday night from 6 - 8 p.m. during the month, Galleria Goes Gourmet offers a flavor of everything delectable including gourmet foods, wines, books, art, home furnishings and accessories as well as entertainment.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=Arial>Festivities will be kicked off on Tuesday, April 3 featuring a Taste of The Promenade. Shoppers can enjoy free sampling from the renowned chefs at each of the Promenade&#8217;s fine restaurants and experience a host of events for even the most avid connoisseur. This includes delicious tastes of smoked sturgeon with lemon dill crème fraiche at Birch Creek, food demonstrations with Chef Vincente Mendoza at Il Fornaio and Phantom of the Opera performances on the patio at Max&#8217;s Café.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=Arial>"Galleria Goes Gourmet highlights Roseville&#8217;s finest selection of restaurants and retailers all in one location &#8211; The Promenade - a relaxing, outdoor streetscape," said Eric Almquist, general manager. "The event activities are free but participants should plan now to stay for dinner and make reservations at their favorite Promenade restaurant." </FONT></P>
<P><FONT face=Arial>Each subsequent Tuesday will serve up unique experiences and the charming ambiance that only The Promenade at Galleria at Roseville can offer. Some of these events include:</FONT></P>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI><FONT face=Arial>"Chef for a Night" activities at Pluto&#8217;s for children ages one to twelve, </FONT></LI>
<LI><FONT face=Arial>A special winemaker&#8217;s dinner at Birch Creek with wines from Domaine Terre Rouge, </FONT></LI>
<LI><FONT face=Arial>Sushi demonstrations and sampling at Rice &amp; Company, and </FONT></LI>
<LI><FONT face=Arial>Food demonstrations at William Sonoma with renowned chef Jeanette Nuss.</FONT></LI></UL></UL>
<P><FONT face=Arial>Unique to the Sacramento region, Galleria at Roseville features <B>The Promenade </B>&#8211; an outdoor, pedestrian streetscape including upscale restaurants and distinctive retailers. Restaurants and stores located within the Promenade include <B>Birch Creek, Il Fornaio, Max&#8217;s Cafe, Rice &amp; Company Asian Bistro, Pluto&#8217;s, Borders Books Music Cafe, Copeland&#8217;s, Home Design, Pottery Barn, Restoration Hardware and Crate &amp; Barrel (opening May 2001). </B>The Promenade is designed as an urban village with street-side cafes, beautiful water features in a nature setting, a children&#8217;s play area and a fireplace. Galleria at Roseville features more then 120 retailers anchored by <B>Nordstrom</B>, <B>Macy&#8217;s</B>, <B>JCPenney</B> and <B>Sears.</P></B></FONT>
<P><FONT face=Arial>For more information on Galleria at Roseville or to schedule an on-site interview, please contact Mitch Zak at (916) 446-6667 or e-mail him at </FONT><A href="mailto:mzak@stoorza.com"><FONT face=Arial>mzak@stoorza.com</FONT></A><FONT face=Arial>. Additional information may also be accessed via the Internet at </FONT><A href="http://www.galleriaroseville.com"><FONT face=Arial>www.galleriaroseville.com</FONT></A></P><FONT face=Arial><FONT size=2>
<P>Galleria at Roseville is owned and developed by Chicago-based Urban Shopping Centers, Inc. (NYSE: URB), a self-administered real estate investment trust (REIT), which is in the business of owning, acquiring, managing, leasing, developing and redeveloping super-regional and regional malls. The company opened Brandon TownCenter in Tampa, Florida in February 1995, Wolfchase Galleria in Memphis, Tennessee in February 1997, a second Tampa-area mall, Citrus Park Town Center, in March 1999, and expects to open Galleria at Roseville on August 25, 2000 and The Streets at Southpoint in Durham, North Carolina in spring 2002. Urban Shopping Centers, Inc. owns interests in several of the premier shopping centers in the United States including Oakbrook Center (Oak Brook, Illinois), Century City Shopping Center &amp; Marketplace (Los Angeles, California), Water Tower Place (Chicago, Illinois), Old Orchard Center (Skokie, Illinois), Copley Place (Boston, Massachusetts),San Francisco Shopping Centre (San Francisco, California), and The Galleria (Houston, Texas), as well as in Urban Retail Properties Co., its property management, leasing and development affiliate. Urban Retail Properties Co. is one of the nation's largest retail property managers, managing more than 59 million square feet of space in 26 states and the District of Columbia.</FONT></FONT></FONT></P>
		<p>&nbsp;</p>
		 
